🔥 1️⃣ == vs eql? vs equal?
🧠 == → Value equality (loose comparison)
5 == 5.0   # => true

Ruby checks logical equality.

🧠 eql? → Hash equality (strict type + value)
5.eql?(5.0)   # => false

Used internally by Hash.

{ 5 => "a" }[5.0]  # => nil

Because Hash uses:

hash

eql?

🧠 equal? → Object identity (same object?)
a = "hello"
b = a
c = "hello"

a.equal?(b)   # => true
a.equal?(c)   # => false

Because c is a different object in memory.

🎯 Summary Table
Method	Checks
==	Value equality
eql?	Value + type equality (used by Hash)
equal?	Same object in memory
🔥 2️⃣ Tricky: puts nil
puts nil

Output:

(blank line)

Why?

Because:

nil.to_s  # => ""

And puts internally does:

puts obj.to_s

So it prints empty string + newline.

